#: ../../../api/sql.rst:2
msgid "`sql` -- SQL string composition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:9
msgid ""
"The module contains objects and functions useful to generate SQL "
"dynamically, in a convenient and safe way. SQL identifiers (e.g. names of "
"tables and fields) cannot be passed to the `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()` "
"method like query arguments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:14
msgid ""
"# This will not work\n"
"table_name = 'my_table'\n"
"cur.execute(\"INSERT INTO %s VALUES (%s, %s)\", [table_name, 10, 20])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:18
msgid ""
"The SQL query should be composed before the arguments are merged, for "
"instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:21
msgid ""
"# This works, but it is not optimal\n"
"table_name = 'my_table'\n"
"cur.execute(\n"
"    \"INSERT INTO %s VALUES (%%s, %%s)\" % table_name,\n"
"    [10, 20])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:27
msgid ""
"This sort of works, but it is an accident waiting to happen: the table name "
"may be an invalid SQL literal and need quoting; even more serious is the "
"security problem in case the table name comes from an untrusted source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:33
msgid ""
"The low-level `~psycopg.pq.Escaping.escape_identifier()` function can be "
"used to escape a single identifier, but it operates on :sql:`bytes` and is "
"cumbersome to use in practice. The `!psycopg.sql` module, described below, "
"is the recommended approach for building dynamic queries safely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:38
msgid ""
"The objects exposed by the `!psycopg.sql` module allow generating SQL "
"statements on the fly, separating clearly the variable parts of the "
"statement from the query parameters::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:42
msgid ""
"from psycopg import sql\n"
"\n"
"cur.execute(\n"
"    sql.SQL(\"INSERT INTO {} VALUES (%s, %s)\")\n"
"        .format(sql.Identifier('my_table')),\n"
"    [10, 20])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:51
msgid "Module usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:53
msgid ""
"Usually you should express the template of your query as an `SQL` instance "
"with ``{}``\\-style placeholders and use `~SQL.format()` to merge the "
"variable parts into them, all of which must be `Composable` subclasses. You "
"can still have ``%s``\\-style placeholders in your query and pass values to "
"`~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`: such value placeholders will be untouched by `!"
"format()`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:60
msgid ""
"query = sql.SQL(\"SELECT {field} FROM {table} WHERE {pkey} = %s\").format(\n"
"    field=sql.Identifier('my_name'),\n"
"    table=sql.Identifier('some_table'),\n"
"    pkey=sql.Identifier('id'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:65
msgid ""
"The resulting object is meant to be passed directly to cursor methods such "
"as `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.executemany()`, `~psycopg."
"Cursor.copy()`, but can also be used to compose a query as a Python string, "
"using the `~Composable.as_string()` method::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:70
msgid ""
"cur.execute(query, (42,))\n"
"full_query = query.as_string(cur)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:73
msgid ""
"If part of your query is a variable sequence of arguments, such as a comma-"
"separated list of field names, you can use the `SQL.join()` method to pass "
"them to the query::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:77
msgid ""
"query = sql.SQL(\"SELECT {fields} FROM {table}\").format(\n"
"    fields=sql.SQL(',').join([\n"
"        sql.Identifier('field1'),\n"
"        sql.Identifier('field2'),\n"
"        sql.Identifier('field3'),\n"
"    ]),\n"
"    table=sql.Identifier('some_table'))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:87
msgid "`!sql` objects"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:89
msgid "The `!sql` objects are in the following inheritance hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:91
msgid "`Composable`: the base class exposing the common interface"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:92
msgid "``|__`` `SQL`: a literal snippet of an SQL query"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:93
msgid ""
"``|__`` `Identifier`: a PostgreSQL identifier or dot-separated sequence of "
"identifiers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:94
msgid "``|__`` `Literal`: a value hardcoded into a query"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:95
msgid ""
"``|__`` `Placeholder`: a `%s`\\ -style placeholder whose value will be added "
"later e.g. by `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:96
msgid "``|__`` `Composed`: a sequence of `!Composable` instances."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable:1
msgid ""
"Abstract base class for objects that can be used to compose an SQL string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable:3
msgid ""
"`!Composable` objects can be joined using the ``+`` operator: the result "
"will be a `Composed` instance containing the objects joined. The operator "
"``*`` is also supported with an integer argument: the result is a `!"
"Composed` instance containing the left argument repeated as many times as "
"requested."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable:9
msgid ""
"`!SQL` and `!Composed` objects can be passed directly to `~psycopg.Cursor."
"execute()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.executemany()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.copy()` in "
"place of the query string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_string:1
msgid "Return the value of the object as string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_bytes:0 psycopg.sql.SQL.format:0
#: ../../../api/sql.rst:0
msgid "Parameters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_string:3
msgid "the context to evaluate the string into."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:105
msgid "The `!context` parameter is optional."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:109
msgid ""
"If a context is not specified, the results are \"generic\" and not tailored "
"for a specific target connection. Details such as the connection encoding "
"and escaping style will not be taken into account."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_bytes:1
msgid "Return the value of the object as bytes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_bytes:3
msgid "the context to evaluate the object into."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composable.as_bytes:6
msgid ""
"The method is automatically invoked by `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`, "
"`~psycopg.Cursor.executemany()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.copy()` if a `!Composable` "
"is passed instead of the query string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:118
msgid "The `!context` parameter is optional. See `as_string` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL:1
msgid "A `Composable` representing a snippet of SQL statement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL:3
msgid ""
"`!SQL` exposes `join()` and `format()` methods useful to create a template "
"where to merge variable parts of a query (for instance field or table names)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL:7
msgid ""
"The `!obj` string doesn't undergo any form of escaping, so it is not "
"suitable to represent variable identifiers or values: you should only use it "
"to pass constant strings representing templates or snippets of SQL "
"statements; use other objects such as `Identifier` or `Literal` to represent "
"variable parts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL:13
msgid ""
"`!SQL` objects can be passed directly to `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`, "
"`~psycopg.Cursor.executemany()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.copy()` in place of the "
"query string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:12 psycopg.sql.Composed.join:6
#: psycopg.sql.Identifier:9 psycopg.sql.Identifier:20 psycopg.sql.Literal:10
#: psycopg.sql.SQL:17 psycopg.sql.SQL.format:21 psycopg.sql.SQL.join:15
msgid "Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL:19
msgid ""
">>> query = sql.SQL(\"SELECT {0} FROM {1}\").format(\n"
"...    sql.SQL(', ').join([sql.Identifier('foo'), sql.Identifier('bar')]),\n"
"...    sql.Identifier('table'))\n"
">>> print(query.as_string(conn))\n"
"SELECT \"foo\", \"bar\" FROM \"table\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:125
msgid ""
"The input object should be a `~typing.LiteralString`. See :pep:`675` for "
"details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:1
msgid "Merge `Composable` objects into a template."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:3
msgid ""
"parameters to replace to numbered (``{0}``, ``{1}``) or auto-numbered (``{}"
"``) placeholders"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:5
msgid "parameters to replace to named (``{name}``) placeholders"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:0
msgid "Returns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:6
msgid "the union of the `!SQL` string with placeholders replaced"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:0
msgid "Return type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:7
msgid "`Composed`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:9
msgid ""
"The method is similar to the Python `str.format()` method: the string "
"template supports auto-numbered (``{}``), numbered (``{0}``, ``{1}``...), "
"and named placeholders (``{name}``), with positional arguments replacing the "
"numbered placeholders and keywords replacing the named ones. However "
"placeholder modifiers (``{0!r}``, ``{0:<10}``) are not supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:16
msgid ""
"If a `!Composable` objects is passed to the template it will be merged "
"according to its `as_string()` method. If any other Python object is passed, "
"it will be wrapped in a `Literal` object and so escaped according to SQL "
"rules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.format:23
msgid ""
">>> print(sql.SQL(\"SELECT * FROM {} WHERE {} = %s\")\n"
"...     .format(sql.Identifier('people'), sql.Identifier('id'))\n"
"...     .as_string(conn))\n"
"SELECT * FROM \"people\" WHERE \"id\" = %s\n"
"\n"
">>> print(sql.SQL(\"SELECT * FROM {tbl} WHERE name = {name}\")\n"
"...     .format(tbl=sql.Identifier('people'), name=\"O'Rourke\"))\n"
"...     .as_string(conn))\n"
"SELECT * FROM \"people\" WHERE name = 'O''Rourke'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:1
msgid "Join a sequence of `Composable`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:3
msgid "the elements to join."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:5
msgid ""
"Use the `!SQL` object's string to separate the elements in `!seq`. Elements "
"that are not `Composable` will be considered `Literal`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:8
msgid ""
"If the arguments are `Template` instance, return a `Template` joining all "
"the items. Note that arguments must either be all templates or none should "
"be."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:12
msgid ""
"Note that `Composed` objects are iterable too, so they can be used as "
"argument for this method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.SQL.join:17
msgid ""
">>> snip = sql.SQL(', ').join(\n"
"...     sql.Identifier(n) for n in ['foo', 'bar', 'baz'])\n"
">>> print(snip.as_string(conn))\n"
"\"foo\", \"bar\", \"baz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:134
msgid ""
"Added support for `~string.templatelib.Template` sequences. See :ref:`nested "
"template strings <tstring-template-nested>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Identifier:1
msgid ""
"A `Composable` representing an SQL identifier or a dot-separated sequence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Identifier:3
msgid ""
"Identifiers usually represent names of database objects, such as tables or "
"fields. PostgreSQL identifiers follow `different rules`__ than SQL string "
"literals for escaping (e.g. they use double quotes instead of single)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Identifier:11
msgid ""
">>> t1 = sql.Identifier(\"foo\")\n"
">>> t2 = sql.Identifier(\"ba'r\")\n"
">>> t3 = sql.Identifier('ba\"z')\n"
">>> print(sql.SQL(', ').join([t1, t2, t3]).as_string(conn))\n"
"\"foo\", \"ba'r\", \"ba\"\"z\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Identifier:17
msgid ""
"Multiple strings can be passed to the object to represent a qualified name, "
"i.e. a dot-separated sequence of identifiers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Identifier:22
msgid ""
">>> query = sql.SQL(\"SELECT {} FROM {}\").format(\n"
"...     sql.Identifier(\"table\", \"field\"),\n"
"...     sql.Identifier(\"schema\", \"table\"))\n"
">>> print(query.as_string(conn))\n"
"SELECT \"table\".\"field\" FROM \"schema\".\"table\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Literal:1
msgid "A `Composable` representing an SQL value to include in a query."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Literal:3
msgid ""
"Usually you will want to include placeholders in the query and pass values "
"as `~cursor.execute()` arguments. If however you really really need to "
"include a literal value in the query you can use this object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Literal:7
msgid ""
"The string returned by `!as_string()` follows the normal :ref:`adaptation "
"rules <types-adaptation>` for Python objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Literal:12
msgid ""
">>> s1 = sql.Literal(\"fo'o\")\n"
">>> s2 = sql.Literal(42)\n"
">>> s3 = sql.Literal(date(2000, 1, 1))\n"
">>> print(sql.SQL(', ').join([s1, s2, s3]).as_string(conn))\n"
"'fo''o', 42, '2000-01-01'::date"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:142
msgid ""
"Add a type cast to the representation if useful in ambiguous context (e.g. "
"``'2000-01-01'::date``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Placeholder:1
msgid "A `Composable` representing a placeholder for query parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Placeholder:3
msgid ""
"If the name is specified, generate a named placeholder (e.g. ``%(name)s``, "
"``%(name)b``), otherwise generate a positional placeholder (e.g. ``%s``, "
"``%b``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Placeholder:7
msgid ""
"The object is useful to generate SQL queries with a variable number of "
"arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Placeholder:10
msgid "Examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Placeholder:12
msgid ""
">>> names = ['foo', 'bar', 'baz']\n"
"\n"
">>> q1 = sql.SQL(\"INSERT INTO my_table ({}) VALUES ({})\").format(\n"
"...     sql.SQL(', ').join(map(sql.Identifier, names)),\n"
"...     sql.SQL(', ').join(sql.Placeholder() * len(names)))\n"
">>> print(q1.as_string(conn))\n"
"INSERT INTO my_table (\"foo\", \"bar\", \"baz\") VALUES (%s, %s, %s)\n"
"\n"
">>> q2 = sql.SQL(\"INSERT INTO my_table ({}) VALUES ({})\").format(\n"
"...     sql.SQL(', ').join(map(sql.Identifier, names)),\n"
"...     sql.SQL(', ').join(map(sql.Placeholder, names)))\n"
">>> print(q2.as_string(conn))\n"
"INSERT INTO my_table (\"foo\", \"bar\", \"baz\") VALUES (%(foo)s, %(bar)s, "
"%(baz)s)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:1
msgid "A `Composable` object made of a sequence of `!Composable`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:3
msgid ""
"The object is usually created using `!Composable` operators and methods "
"(such as the `SQL.format()` method). `!Composed` objects can be passed "
"directly to `~psycopg.Cursor.execute()`, `~psycopg.Cursor.executemany()`, "
"`~psycopg.Cursor.copy()` in place of the query string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:8
msgid ""
"It is also possible to create a `!Composed` directly specifying a sequence "
"of objects as arguments: if they are not `!Composable` they will be wrapped "
"in a `Literal`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:14
msgid ""
">>> comp = sql.Composed(\n"
"...     [sql.SQL(\"INSERT INTO \"), sql.Identifier(\"table\")])\n"
">>> print(comp.as_string(conn))\n"
"INSERT INTO \"table\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed:19
msgid ""
"`!Composed` objects are iterable (so they can be used in `SQL.join` for "
"instance)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed.join:1
msgid ""
"Return a new `!Composed` interposing the `!joiner` with the `!Composed` "
"items."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed.join:3
msgid ""
"The `!joiner` must be a `SQL` or a string which will be interpreted as an "
"`SQL`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.Composed.join:8
msgid ""
">>> fields = sql.Identifier('foo') + sql.Identifier('bar')  # a Composed\n"
">>> print(fields.join(', ').as_string(conn))\n"
"\"foo\", \"bar\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/sql.rst:154
msgid "Utility functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/sql.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.sql.as_string:1
msgid "Convert an object to a string according to SQL rules."
